WEBVTT

00:53.930 --> 00:55.515
(RAIN PATTERING)

00:56.307 --> 00:58.059
(HORSE NEIGHS SOFTLY)

01:06.526 --> 01:09.153
(SOFTLY) Shh. Hey.

01:12.782 --> 01:15.076
BATH S H E <i>BA: Bathsheba Everdene.</i>

01:15.785 --> 01:17.120
<i>Bathsheba.</i>

01:18.913 --> 01:20.665
<i>The name has always
sounded strange to me.</i>

01:20.748 --> 01:22.250
<i>I don't like to hear it
said out loud.</i>

01:25.128 --> 01:27.672
<i>My parents died
when I was very young,</i>

01:27.755 --> 01:30.466
<i>so there's no one to ask
where it came from.</i>

01:31.384 --> 01:34.304
<i>I've grown accustomed
to being on my own.</i>

01:34.637 --> 01:37.432
<i>Some say even too accustomed.</i>

01:38.433 --> 01:41.102
<i>Too independent.</i>

02:21.225 --> 02:22.226
(URGES HORSE)

02:58.596 --> 03:00.932
(DOG BARKING)

03:13.695 --> 03:15.029
GABRIEL: Miss!

03:18.533 --> 03:19.826
Miss!

03:20.576 --> 03:22.120
(SHEEP BLEATING)

03:33.089 --> 03:34.132
(PANTING)

03:35.508 --> 03:37.051
My scarf.

03:37.635 --> 03:39.011
I lost it.

03:40.138 --> 03:41.764
You must be Farmer Oak.

03:41.848 --> 03:43.474
Gabriel, yes.

03:43.891 --> 03:45.601
My aunt's told me
about you.

03:45.685 --> 03:47.478
I'm working on her farm
for the winter.

03:51.065 --> 03:52.650
This is your land.

03:54.235 --> 03:56.320
I'm trespassing.

03:56.404 --> 03:58.239
You're welcome here.

04:11.335 --> 04:12.712
Good afternoon,
Farmer Oak.

04:13.004 --> 04:14.881
Good afternoon, miss.

04:34.776 --> 04:36.194
(GABRIEL WHISTLES)

04:44.911 --> 04:46.370
GABRIEL: Come by, George.

04:46.788 --> 04:50.291
George, away!
Enough, George!

04:50.416 --> 04:51.876
(YOUNG GEORGE BARKING)
Enough!

04:52.960 --> 04:54.962
Stand. Stand.

04:55.379 --> 04:56.756
George, stand.

04:57.256 --> 04:58.382
(BARKING CONTINUES)

04:58.549 --> 04:59.717
Away!

05:00.134 --> 05:01.302
Away!

05:02.470 --> 05:04.764
George, away!

05:06.557 --> 05:08.476
He doesn't know
when to stop,
Young George.

05:08.976 --> 05:10.353
What's this one called?

05:10.436 --> 05:11.687
Old George.

05:11.771 --> 05:13.064
(BATHSHEBA LAUGHS)

05:14.440 --> 05:15.900
Old George.

05:16.317 --> 05:17.902
So you find me
amusing, do you?

05:17.985 --> 05:20.238
(YOUNG GEORGE
CONTINUES BARKING)

05:29.080 --> 05:30.164
(WHINNIES)

06:07.785 --> 06:09.871
Goodness,
it's Mr. Oak.

06:20.673 --> 06:22.967
MRS. HURST: ...and after that
she was gonna be a governess.

06:23.050 --> 06:24.468
But she was far too wild.

06:24.635 --> 06:26.387
Always has been.

06:26.470 --> 06:27.471
Oh!

06:34.729 --> 06:38.065
Miss Bathsheba Everdene.

06:39.025 --> 06:41.152
I've brought you a lamb.

06:41.652 --> 06:43.529
Oh!
(LAMB BLEATING)

06:44.322 --> 06:48.993
Thank you, Mr. Oak.
He's such a dear thing.

06:49.160 --> 06:51.370
He's come too soon
and won't last the winter,

06:51.495 --> 06:53.664
so I thought you'd
like to rear it instead.

06:54.040 --> 06:56.250
Thank you,
that's very kind.

06:57.084 --> 06:59.253
I'll make some tea.

07:02.340 --> 07:04.008
The lamb is not
why I came.

07:04.175 --> 07:05.843
Go on.

07:07.595 --> 07:08.638
(CHUCKLES)

07:08.721 --> 07:11.349
Well, Miss Everdene,
I wanted to ask...

07:11.933 --> 07:13.684
Would you like
to marry me?

07:16.938 --> 07:18.522
I've never asked
anyone before.

07:18.773 --> 07:20.024
(CHUCKLES)

07:20.733 --> 07:21.734
No.

07:22.902 --> 07:24.695
I should hope not.

07:26.030 --> 07:27.198
Well...

07:28.240 --> 07:30.785
Perhaps I, erm, I should...

07:32.787 --> 07:34.038
Perhaps I should leave.
Mr. Oak,

07:34.121 --> 07:35.873
there are things to consider.

07:37.291 --> 07:39.043
Is someone waiting for you?

07:39.377 --> 07:42.546
No, but that doesn't
mean I'll marry you.

07:43.756 --> 07:45.091
Good day to you, then.

07:54.100 --> 07:55.726
Mr. Oak!

07:56.435 --> 07:59.605
Mr. Oak! Wait!

08:02.400 --> 08:05.152
I didn't say I wouldn't
marry you, either.

08:05.403 --> 08:07.279
(PANTING)

08:07.405 --> 08:09.115
I haven't ever really
thought about it.

08:09.740 --> 08:12.910
I have 100 acres
and 200 sheep.

08:14.662 --> 08:17.581
If I pay off the money,
the farm is ours.

08:19.083 --> 08:21.335
You could have a piano
in a year or two.

08:21.460 --> 08:24.755
Flowers and birds
and a frame for cucumbers.

08:25.089 --> 08:26.632
A baby or two.

08:26.757 --> 08:27.925
Mr. Oak...
Or more.

08:29.260 --> 08:31.095
I will always
be there for you.

08:32.804 --> 08:34.932
Mr. Oak, I don't
want a husband.

08:35.640 --> 08:38.144
I'd hate to be
some man's property.

08:39.477 --> 08:41.063
I shouldn't mind being
a bride at a wedding

08:41.147 --> 08:43.107
if I could be one
without getting a husband.

08:43.524 --> 08:45.359
That's stupid talk.

08:47.028 --> 08:49.280
You are better off
than I, Mr. Oak.

08:49.780 --> 08:52.033
I have an education
and nothing more.

08:52.158 --> 08:53.784
You could do much,
much better than me.

08:53.868 --> 08:55.327
That's not the reason.

09:00.374 --> 09:01.459
I'm too independent
for you.

09:01.625 --> 09:02.626
(LAUGHS)

09:03.377 --> 09:04.545
If I ever were to marry,

09:04.628 --> 09:05.838
I'd want somebody to tame me

09:05.963 --> 09:07.631
and you'd never
be able to do it.

09:09.467 --> 09:11.552
You'd grow to despise me.

09:14.013 --> 09:15.473
I would not.

09:17.683 --> 09:19.018
Even

09:23.647 --> 09:25.900
Good-bye, Miss Everdene.

09:52.051 --> 09:54.095
(OLD GEORGE WHINING SOFTLY)

09:55.763 --> 09:57.848
(YOUNG GEORGE BARKING OUTSIDE)

09:59.350 --> 10:00.726
(WHINING CONTINUES)

10:08.692 --> 10:10.194
(BARKING)

10:11.362 --> 10:12.363
(GROWLING)

10:14.031 --> 10:15.533
(SHEEP BLEATING)

10:17.576 --> 10:19.870
(BARKING CONTINUES)

10:25.876 --> 10:27.419
(BARKS)
What is it, old boy?

10:27.545 --> 10:28.921
(WHINING)

10:30.381 --> 10:31.924
Stay here.

10:35.886 --> 10:37.429
Stay here, Old George.

10:37.555 --> 10:39.306
(BARKING)
Stay here.

10:48.732 --> 10:50.234
George!

10:54.113 --> 10:55.823
(YOUNG GEORGE
BARKING <i>m</i> DISTANCE)

11:02.496 --> 11:04.582
George!

11:04.665 --> 11:07.918
(DISTANT BLEATING AND BARKING)

11:21.307 --> 11:23.976
(BLEATING FRANTICALLY)

11:25.186 --> 11:26.270
(BARKING)

11:31.525 --> 11:33.444
(PANTING)

11:36.447 --> 11:38.324
(BARKING CONTINUES)

11:51.045 --> 11:52.630
No!

12:20.699 --> 12:22.910
(SCREAMING)

12:37.591 --> 12:39.218
(GUNSHOT)
(THUD)

13:00.239 --> 13:01.448
It's all yours.

13:12.710 --> 13:14.878
We take no pleasure in this.

13:15.754 --> 13:16.839
(PANTING)

13:16.922 --> 13:19.049
BAILIFF: We wish
you well, Mr. Oak.

13:34.106 --> 13:35.274
MRS. HURST: Bathsheba.

13:40.112 --> 13:41.613
What is it?

13:42.239 --> 13:45.951
My love. It's your
poor uncle's will.

13:46.910 --> 13:48.454
What does it say?

13:49.913 --> 13:51.290
Read it.

13:52.499 --> 13:53.917
Read!

13:55.836 --> 13:59.757
He's left you everything.
It's all yours.

14:00.632 --> 14:01.842
Oh!

14:02.634 --> 14:04.595
Oh, my goodness.

14:06.180 --> 14:08.349
Take care,
you hear.

14:16.482 --> 14:17.858
Walk on.

14:23.530 --> 14:24.865
Bye.

14:43.801 --> 14:45.094
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

14:45.177 --> 14:47.388
So who will
join us, lads?

14:48.180 --> 14:49.640
Which one of you fine boys

14:49.723 --> 14:51.350
will put on
the scarlet uniform

14:51.475 --> 14:54.812
and proudly serve
his Queen and country?

14:55.813 --> 14:57.314
See the world.

14:58.482 --> 15:01.318
Form an orderly line,
gentlemen, at the front.

15:01.652 --> 15:02.653
This gentleman
in the straw hat,

15:02.736 --> 15:03.779
step forward, sir.

15:03.862 --> 15:05.489
That's my sweetheart,
right there.

15:05.989 --> 15:09.326
You, sir,
next to the pretty lady.

15:09.910 --> 15:11.870
There's a good strong
figure of a man.

15:12.246 --> 15:13.580
Join us, sir.

15:13.997 --> 15:15.916
Go on. You'd make
a fine soldier.

15:15.999 --> 15:17.876
Always room in the ranks for
a gentleman of your caliber.

15:18.001 --> 15:19.586
FAN NY: It's a roof
over your head. Food.

15:22.172 --> 15:24.383
DOGGETT: Who wants
a fine wage?

15:24.508 --> 15:25.843
Excuse me.

15:25.926 --> 15:28.595
You might try Weatherbury.
If you're looking for work,

15:28.679 --> 15:30.806
there's a farm there
needs all the help it can get.

15:30.889 --> 15:32.516
DOGGETT: Yes.
The young lad there.

15:32.599 --> 15:34.601
I will. Thank you.

15:34.685 --> 15:35.936
DOGGETT: And your
friend as well.

15:36.019 --> 15:37.855
You should have a cloak
for a day like this.

15:39.690 --> 15:41.233
FANNY: Francis
will take care of me.

15:43.777 --> 15:45.446
We are to be married soon.

15:46.405 --> 15:47.781
Good-bye.

15:47.906 --> 15:49.491
DOGGETT: Come on,
a decent wage.

15:49.575 --> 15:51.118
Make your family proud.

15:51.243 --> 15:54.413
Food,sheHen
Who will join us?

16:33.452 --> 16:35.287
(DISTANT SHOUTING, INDISTINCT)

16:41.084 --> 16:42.961
(SHOUTING CONTINUES)

16:47.299 --> 16:49.593
FARMHAND 1: Go and wake up
the other farms!

16:49.676 --> 16:51.887
Get them down here!
We need more hands!

16:51.970 --> 16:53.138
FARMHAND 2: We need
more men now!

16:53.263 --> 16:54.264
Wake them up!

16:55.015 --> 16:57.518
FARMHAND 1: Go and get
the Smith brothers first.

16:57.643 --> 17:00.145
FARMHAND 3: Protect yourself,
the fire's spreading!

17:00.270 --> 17:01.313
(FARMHANDS COUGHING)

17:01.438 --> 17:02.814
Who's in charge here?

17:02.940 --> 17:06.193
We're losing the ricks!
(COUGHING) The rick is lost.

17:06.777 --> 17:08.529
We need to save the barn.
Come on, help me!

17:09.320 --> 17:12.574
Come on, get some more water!
Get some more water!

17:12.657 --> 17:13.659
(FARMHANDS CLAMORING)

17:13.784 --> 17:16.286
We need to push
this out. Come on!

17:16.369 --> 17:17.663
Heave!

17:19.790 --> 17:21.458
ALL: Heave!

17:21.791 --> 17:23.126
Heave!

17:24.502 --> 17:26.922
GABRIEL: Come on, push!

17:27.005 --> 17:29.132
(MEN GRUNTING)

17:36.014 --> 17:37.808
(FARMHANDS CONTINUE SHOUTING)

17:49.653 --> 17:52.322
FARMHAND 1: Everybody out!
Everybody out!

17:56.702 --> 17:58.954
FARMHAND 2: Water!
More over here!

17:59.037 --> 18:00.080
The barn's going UP!

18:00.163 --> 18:02.499
FARMHAND 3: Get the sacks out,
the root's about to go!

18:06.545 --> 18:08.338
(PANTING)

18:18.849 --> 18:20.684
What's he doing
up there?

18:20.767 --> 18:23.353
OLDER MAN: We lose the barn,
we lose everything.

18:49.046 --> 18:50.547
(PANTING)

18:54.885 --> 18:56.720
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

19:03.644 --> 19:06.188
JACOB: Joseph,
bring those brooms over

19:06.271 --> 19:07.898
and let's get
this sorted out.

19:08.899 --> 19:11.735
Look sharp, men,
the farmer's here.

19:25.916 --> 19:27.918
Mr. Oak, is that you?

19:32.798 --> 19:34.257
Perhaps you want
a shepherd, ma'am?

19:38.303 --> 19:40.931
I owe you an immense
debt, Mr. Oak.

19:41.515 --> 19:43.809
If I'd have lost all of this,
I'd have lost my farm.

19:43.934 --> 19:44.976
Your farm?

19:45.435 --> 19:46.687
My inheritance.

19:46.770 --> 19:49.690
My home, too, for a while
when my parents died.

19:51.024 --> 19:53.860
When my uncle passed away,
he left it to me.

19:54.945 --> 19:57.614
Of course,
it's a little ragged now,

19:58.448 --> 20:01.284
but this once used to be
the finest farm for miles.

20:01.451 --> 20:03.954
And I intend
to make it so again.

20:05.455 --> 20:06.957
Perhaps you find
the idea preposterous.

20:07.666 --> 20:10.127
Inolonger
have that luxury.

20:11.795 --> 20:14.548
I'm truly sorry to hear
of your loss, Mr. Oak,

20:14.631 --> 20:16.091
but if our
reversal of fortune

20:16.174 --> 20:17.592
causes you
any embarrassment...

20:17.676 --> 20:20.053
Not at all, ma'am.

20:24.808 --> 20:27.227
BATHSHEBA: Billy Smallbury?
9 and 8 pence.

20:29.312 --> 20:31.064
Joseph Poorgrass?

20:31.565 --> 20:32.691
WOMAN: Go on, Joseph.

20:32.858 --> 20:34.025
MAN: Go on, lad.

20:34.151 --> 20:35.736
(WHISPERS) Hat off.

20:36.987 --> 20:38.530
And what do you do, Joseph?

20:38.697 --> 20:40.282
I does general things.

20:40.365 --> 20:41.616
And in spring
I shoot the rooks

20:41.700 --> 20:42.826
and help at pig killing, sir.

20:42.909 --> 20:43.910
(FAINT LAUGHTER)

20:43.994 --> 20:45.036
I mean ma'am.

20:46.580 --> 20:50.417
7 and 9 pence.
And another 9 because I'm new.

20:50.500 --> 20:52.335
Thank you, ma'am.

20:56.548 --> 20:58.550
Now, Fanny Robbin?

21:00.844 --> 21:02.929
Where is Fanny Robbin?

21:03.722 --> 21:04.723
Where is she?

21:05.891 --> 21:08.059
She's run away, ma'am.

21:08.685 --> 21:10.479
She's gone off
with a soldier, ma'am.

21:10.562 --> 21:12.731
Not a soldier, a sergeant.

21:17.027 --> 21:18.528
Bailiff Pennyways?

21:18.695 --> 21:20.113
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

21:23.533 --> 21:26.119
Here is 10 shillings
and a further 10.

21:26.536 --> 21:28.079
(SOFTLY) Why?

21:29.039 --> 21:31.625
This ends our association.
You are dismissed.

21:32.042 --> 21:33.585
I beg pardon, miss?

21:33.710 --> 21:34.711
When my uncle was alive,

21:34.795 --> 21:36.922
this was a fine,
productive farm.

21:37.380 --> 21:39.716
Since his death,
it has fallen into ruin.

21:41.218 --> 21:42.719
I can only assume...
Now see here, miss.

21:42.803 --> 21:43.929
You can't get rid
of people like that.

21:44.054 --> 21:45.055
I have resolved
to have no bailiff at all,

21:45.138 --> 21:46.181
I have decided
to manage everything.

21:46.264 --> 21:48.266
Mr. Pennyways, if you'll
listen to me for a moment.

21:48.391 --> 21:51.311
Mr. Pennyways, a fire
threatened to destroy the barn

21:51.394 --> 21:53.563
and you are
nowhere to be found.

21:58.443 --> 22:01.488
I have no use for a man
like you, Mr. Pennyways.

22:02.572 --> 22:03.615
You are dismissed.

22:13.124 --> 22:14.960
PENNYWAYS: Get out
while you can, if I were you.

22:17.170 --> 22:18.588
(ALL MURMURING)

22:26.096 --> 22:27.931
Now you've all met
our new shepherd, Mr. Oak.

22:29.808 --> 22:31.935
You understand
your duties, Mr. Oak?

22:33.144 --> 22:35.146
If I don't, I'll ask, ma'am.

22:40.944 --> 22:44.114
From now on, you have
a mistress, not a master.

22:44.865 --> 22:46.324
I don't yet know
my talents in farming,

22:46.449 --> 22:47.951
but I shall do my best.

22:48.952 --> 22:50.287
Don't suppose,
because I'm a woman,

22:50.370 --> 22:51.454
I don't know
the difference between

22:51.538 --> 22:53.164
bad goings-on and good.

22:53.290 --> 22:55.458
I shall be up
before you're awake.

22:56.042 --> 22:57.794
I shall be a-field
before you are up.

22:58.712 --> 23:01.464
It is my intention
to astonish you all.

23:04.467 --> 23:05.969
Back to work, please.

23:08.305 --> 23:10.140
(MURMURING RESUMES)

23:18.565 --> 23:20.483
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

23:25.322 --> 23:27.198
Perhaps I should
wait here?

23:27.324 --> 23:28.575
No.

23:29.159 --> 23:32.662
Nonsense, Liddy.
You're my companion.

23:32.746 --> 23:33.747
All of these?

23:33.914 --> 23:34.915
All of them.

23:37.208 --> 23:38.209
Head high, Liddy.

23:38.335 --> 23:40.170
If they stare,
do not hesitate.

23:41.338 --> 23:43.423
(MAN SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)

23:47.510 --> 23:50.096
Remember, we have as much
right to be here as anyone.

23:54.434 --> 23:55.685
Good morning.

23:56.394 --> 23:58.438
(MEN CHATTERING INDISTINCTLY)

24:00.941 --> 24:02.692
(CHATTERING STOPS)

24:12.535 --> 24:14.079
Liddy, if you
lay things out.

24:14.245 --> 24:15.789
Yes, miss.

24:16.873 --> 24:20.460
Gentlemen, shall we
get back to business?

24:21.962 --> 24:23.755
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

24:30.053 --> 24:31.429
There you go, sir.

24:31.554 --> 24:33.056
If you feel it,
you can feel the quality.

24:33.723 --> 24:34.724
This is fine
grain, miss.

24:34.808 --> 24:35.850
Thank you.

24:38.561 --> 24:40.730
Perhaps we should
leave, miss.

24:44.109 --> 24:45.819
But none of it
as good as this lot.

24:45.902 --> 24:47.070
It's good stuff,
I'll grant you that.

24:47.237 --> 24:48.488
Well, it's up to you.
If you wanna go elsewhere...

24:48.571 --> 24:49.656
No,no,no“.

24:49.739 --> 24:50.949
Farmer Stone?

24:51.574 --> 24:55.078
It's Miss Everdene.
Farmer Everdene's niece.

24:56.579 --> 24:58.915
He talked about you
with such great admiration.

25:01.751 --> 25:03.420
Of course, you're welcome
to try elsewhere,

25:03.503 --> 25:06.673
but I think you'll find
the grain as good
as it's ever been.

25:09.509 --> 25:10.802
(SNIFFS)

25:11.261 --> 25:12.637
Mr. Stone?
How much?

25:12.762 --> 25:14.597
£5 a quarter.

25:14.764 --> 25:16.641
£3-10 shillings.

25:16.933 --> 25:18.101
It's the same grain,
Mr. Stone.

25:18.184 --> 25:20.478
You paid my uncle £5.

25:20.603 --> 25:22.439
£340.

25:24.315 --> 25:26.693
BATHSHEBA: This gentleman
will pay me the proper price.

25:29.279 --> 25:31.114
MAN: Apparently not, no.

25:31.614 --> 25:32.657
£4.

25:32.782 --> 25:33.783
£4-10.

25:33.950 --> 25:35.368
£4-05.

25:36.703 --> 25:38.038
Perhaps I should move on.

25:38.872 --> 25:41.041
Liddy, would you help me
with this gentleman?

25:41.124 --> 25:42.542
Of course.

25:43.293 --> 25:45.295
Perhaps you'd
like a sample?

25:45.795 --> 25:47.672
How much?
£5 a quarter.

25:48.465 --> 25:50.133
Very well.

25:52.135 --> 25:53.845
£4-10.

25:55.472 --> 25:57.015
(PEOPLE APPLAUDING)

26:02.979 --> 26:04.814
(CHURCH ORGAN PLAYING)

26:04.898 --> 26:08.318
<i>Jerusalem the golden</i>

26:08.485 --> 26:13.531
<i>With milk and honey blest</i>

26:14.157 --> 26:19.662
<i>Beneath thy contemplation</i>

26:19.996 --> 26:25.001
<i>Sink heart and voice oppressed</i>

26:25.919 --> 26:31.049
He's rich, he's handsome.
He sends the local girls mad.

26:31.508 --> 26:34.969
The Taylor sisters
worked on him for two years.

26:35.053 --> 26:37.222
Jane Perkins spent £20
on new clothes

26:37.347 --> 26:38.431
and might as well have

26:38.515 --> 26:40.558
thrown the money
out the window.

26:42.769 --> 26:46.606
It's said, when he was young,
his sweetheartjilted him.

26:48.358 --> 26:50.360
People always say that.

26:50.860 --> 26:54.030
Women don'tjilt men.
Men jilt us.

26:54.531 --> 26:56.866
Did someone
jilt you, miss?

26:57.200 --> 26:59.077
Certainly not.

27:02.539 --> 27:04.707
A man did ask
to marry me once.

27:04.791 --> 27:06.042
Some time ago.

27:06.459 --> 27:08.920
But I was too restless
to be tied down.

27:09.045 --> 27:12.382
What a luxury,
to have a choice.

27:13.716 --> 27:17.595
"Kiss my foot, sir, my face
is for mouths of consequence."

27:17.720 --> 27:19.639
It wasn't
like that at all.

27:20.557 --> 27:21.891
LIDDYI Why?

27:22.976 --> 27:24.435
Did you love him?

27:24.978 --> 27:27.397
No, but I rather liked him.

27:28.481 --> 27:30.733
Anyway, it's impossible now.

27:30.817 --> 27:32.068
(CONGREGATION
CONTINUES SINGING)

27:33.820 --> 27:34.946
(SQUAWKING)

27:37.282 --> 27:38.491
(GUNSHOT)

27:44.455 --> 27:45.748
Mr. Boldwood.

27:46.249 --> 27:47.417
Don't shoot me, please.

27:48.168 --> 27:50.420
I had no intention
of shooting you.

27:52.755 --> 27:55.258
It's Miss Everdene.
Your neighbor.

27:56.593 --> 27:58.803
Farmer Everdene's niece.

28:02.015 --> 28:03.057
I'm managing the farm
alone now.

28:03.141 --> 28:04.142
Perhaps you've heard?

28:04.309 --> 28:06.644
Yes, I'm sure
you'll do very well.

28:08.354 --> 28:09.522
In the circumstances.

28:13.359 --> 28:16.738
Well, as you say,
we're neighbors.

28:16.821 --> 28:17.864
(CLICKS TONGUE)

28:17.947 --> 28:19.324
(HORSE GALLOPING)

28:29.542 --> 28:31.377
LIDDY: Look what
I've got here.

28:32.629 --> 28:33.630
What is it?

28:33.796 --> 28:34.797
Listen to this.

28:34.881 --> 28:36.633
"The rose is red
The violet blue

28:36.799 --> 28:39.802
"Carnation's sweet
And so are you"

28:41.638 --> 28:43.348
It's a Valentine's card.

28:43.473 --> 28:45.642
I'm going to send it
to Joseph Poorgrass

28:45.725 --> 28:48.394
just to see the look
of panic on his stupid face.

28:48.519 --> 28:51.356
Poor boy. It's a little bit
far-fetched, isn't it?

28:52.023 --> 28:54.651
What about
Mr. Oak, then?

28:54.734 --> 28:57.362
No. Not Mr. Oak.

28:58.821 --> 29:00.490
Imagine if we sent it
to Mr. Boldwood.

29:02.408 --> 29:04.994
Ignoring you like that,
all high and mighty.

29:05.662 --> 29:07.247
Mr. Boldwood?

29:08.998 --> 29:10.583
Perhaps not?

29:11.000 --> 29:12.335
Why not?

29:12.502 --> 29:15.004
Because I don't think
he'll see the humor.

29:15.672 --> 29:16.673
(LAUGHING)
Perhaps he wouldn't,

29:16.756 --> 29:18.007
perhaps it's too much.

29:18.091 --> 29:20.218
Mr. Boldwood.

29:20.385 --> 29:22.512
You're right.
Perhaps it is.

29:23.680 --> 29:25.431
So we're gonna
toss for it.

29:25.515 --> 29:26.516
Liddy!

29:26.599 --> 29:27.934
Come on.

29:30.436 --> 29:32.188
Open, Joseph.

29:32.355 --> 29:34.065
No, Jan Coggan.

29:34.232 --> 29:38.194
Open, Jan Coggan.
Closed, Boldwood.

29:38.945 --> 29:40.029
(LIDDY YELPS)

30:47.847 --> 30:49.432
Sergeant Troy, 11:00.

30:49.599 --> 30:51.184
Yes, Sergeant Troy. And?

30:51.309 --> 30:53.478
Miss Fanny Robbin.

30:53.644 --> 30:55.813
Welcome. Step down the front.

30:55.897 --> 30:57.648
(CHOIR SINGING HYMN)

31:02.612 --> 31:04.155
(EXHALES SHAKILY)

31:28.763 --> 31:30.181
(WHISPERS)
Where is she?

31:30.348 --> 31:31.766
I don't know.

31:32.475 --> 31:33.935
(DOOR OPENS)

31:34.018 --> 31:35.436
FEMALE PARISHIONER:
Here she comes.

31:40.775 --> 31:42.026
Oh.

31:51.452 --> 31:53.246
DOGGETT: (WHISPERS)
Sorry I'm late, old boy.

31:54.497 --> 31:55.832
Not long now.

32:12.056 --> 32:13.391
(EXHALES DEEPLY)

32:17.228 --> 32:20.565
Dearly beloved, we are
gathered here in the sight...

32:20.648 --> 32:21.649
(PEOPLE MURMURING)

32:25.445 --> 32:27.447
I can only wait
a few more minutes.

32:27.530 --> 32:28.906
She'll be here.

32:55.683 --> 32:57.518
(WHISPERS) What do you
think is happening?

32:58.352 --> 33:00.771
DOGGETT: I don't think
she's coming, old boy.

33:27.173 --> 33:29.175
(SHEEP BLEATING)

33:30.760 --> 33:33.429
Come on. Go on, off you go.
That's it. Go on.

33:34.096 --> 33:35.348
Morning, my love.

33:35.515 --> 33:36.766
Come on.

33:36.849 --> 33:38.726
(TALKING INDISTINCTLY)

33:39.936 --> 33:41.562
Bring them in, John.

33:46.943 --> 33:47.985
GABRIEL: Grab this one.

33:48.069 --> 33:49.320
Miss Everdene's here now,

33:49.403 --> 33:50.488
so you better do
your best work.

33:50.571 --> 33:52.031
I'm looking
at you, Coggan.

33:52.114 --> 33:53.574
COGGAN: Yeah,
you keep quiet, Liddy.

33:53.658 --> 33:54.659
(LAUGHING)

34:02.625 --> 34:03.668
What you doing?

34:06.504 --> 34:08.380
Perhaps you'd care
to lend a hand?

34:09.340 --> 34:10.757
You don't
think I would?

34:10.925 --> 34:12.301
No, you wouldn't.

34:13.678 --> 34:15.137
Come here.

34:19.475 --> 34:21.018
COGGAN: There,
she's getting in.

34:21.101 --> 34:22.603
(ALL CHEERING)

34:23.437 --> 34:24.981
Well done, ma'am.

34:47.420 --> 34:50.422
COGGAN: Gangway through.
Hey, Joseph. Joseph, look.

35:28.169 --> 35:30.379
Good morning,
Mr. Boldwood.

35:33.341 --> 35:34.592
Miss Everdene.

35:34.675 --> 35:38.679
Mr. Boldwood wondered if
he might have a word with you.

35:42.266 --> 35:45.478
Mr. Boldwood.
Of course.

35:46.604 --> 35:51.025
WILLIAM: One thousand acres.
A mix of arable and livestock.

35:51.692 --> 35:53.069
Adjacent to Everdene.

35:53.486 --> 35:56.906
An orchard. Glasshouse.

35:58.157 --> 36:00.117
I have some
interesting pigs.
(LAUGHS)

36:02.703 --> 36:04.872
Some other time,
perhaps.

36:09.960 --> 36:11.295
Thank you.

36:22.306 --> 36:24.975
You have a very
beautiful house.

36:30.481 --> 36:31.774
Mr. Boldwood?

36:34.819 --> 36:36.195
Miss Everdene.

36:38.030 --> 36:39.532
I want

36:40.700 --> 36:43.703
very much,
more than anything,

36:44.787 --> 36:46.580
to have you as my wife.

36:47.373 --> 36:50.376
Miss Everdene,
marry me.

36:54.588 --> 36:55.589
(STAMMERING) I...

36:57.341 --> 36:59.343
I feel...

37:01.887 --> 37:05.057
Though I respect you
very much,

37:07.435 --> 37:10.730
I do not feel
what would justify me

37:14.358 --> 37:16.652
in accepting your offer.

37:20.698 --> 37:24.201
I have known
disappointments before,

37:25.786 --> 37:27.621
but I would never have
asked in this instance

37:27.705 --> 37:29.498
had I not been, er,

37:30.624 --> 37:32.376
led to believe...

37:33.711 --> 37:37.339
Unless...
Unless I am mistaken.

37:39.049 --> 37:40.593
BATHSHEBA: The valentine.

37:41.969 --> 37:43.053
No, you're not mistaken,

37:43.137 --> 37:45.264
but I should
never have sent it.

37:46.599 --> 37:49.393
Forgive me, it was thoughtless
to disturb your peace of mind.

37:49.477 --> 37:50.978
So you meant it as a joke?

37:51.061 --> 37:54.273
No. No, not as a joke.

37:55.858 --> 37:59.737
Not exactly.
It was impetuous.

37:59.862 --> 38:00.988
I see.

38:02.198 --> 38:04.241
Perhaps you think
I am too old?

38:04.492 --> 38:07.328
But I will care for you
more than anyone your own age.

38:07.828 --> 38:09.705
I'm sure you would...
I will protect you.

38:10.790 --> 38:13.209
You shall have dresses,

38:14.335 --> 38:17.505
a Qig- Uh, a piano.

38:20.883 --> 38:22.176
I amuse you?

38:23.969 --> 38:25.346
No.

38:26.555 --> 38:28.015
It's only...

38:29.183 --> 38:31.185
I have a piano.

38:32.645 --> 38:35.105
And I have my own farm.

38:36.232 --> 38:37.858
And I have no need
for a husband,

38:38.859 --> 38:41.987
no matter how honored
lam by the offer.

38:47.409 --> 38:49.787
I think I'd like
to return home.

38:49.954 --> 38:52.873
Yes, er... I'll, er...

38:53.582 --> 38:55.918
I'll get someone
to drive you.

38:56.502 --> 38:59.046
Mr. Boldwood,
I've made you miserable.

38:59.129 --> 39:00.714
It was very wicked of me.

39:00.798 --> 39:02.800
Will you reconsider?

39:05.594 --> 39:07.429
Let me think.

39:09.974 --> 39:11.183
Yes.

39:12.351 --> 39:14.311
Yes, I'll give you time.

39:15.479 --> 39:17.147
I will wait.

39:42.673 --> 39:44.216
You're working
late, Mr. Oak.

39:49.388 --> 39:51.307
Will you teach me?

39:52.516 --> 39:53.809
Here.

39:55.311 --> 39:56.812
Spin the wheel.

39:57.605 --> 39:59.607
Incline it, like that.

40:00.941 --> 40:03.110
And slide it gently.
Spin the wheel.

40:05.738 --> 40:09.199
Bit faster. Like that.
Very good.

40:10.743 --> 40:12.036
Now slide it.

40:12.202 --> 40:13.537
I... It's...

40:14.580 --> 40:16.957
Getting stuck.

40:23.923 --> 40:25.633
I wanted to ask,

40:26.216 --> 40:28.469
did the men say anything
today about Mr. Boldwood?

40:28.552 --> 40:29.637
They did.

40:29.803 --> 40:30.846
What did they say?

40:31.138 --> 40:34.141
That you'd be married
before the end of the year.

40:34.475 --> 40:35.976
Come on.

40:37.102 --> 40:38.145
(CHUCKLES)

40:38.228 --> 40:40.147
Well, I'd like you
to contradict it, to the men.

40:41.065 --> 40:42.566
Well, Bathsheba...

40:42.733 --> 40:44.276
"Miss Everdene," please.

40:47.071 --> 40:49.365
If Mr. Boldwood did really
speak of marriage,

40:49.490 --> 40:51.700
I'm not going to tell
stories just to please you.

40:53.327 --> 40:55.454
I just said I wanted you
to mention to the men

40:55.537 --> 40:57.790
that it might not be true
I was going to marry him.

40:57.873 --> 41:00.042
I could say that
if you wish.

41:00.125 --> 41:02.086
But I could also give you an
opinion on what you've done.

41:02.169 --> 41:05.089
I dare say, but I don't want
your opinion, Mr. Oak.

41:07.633 --> 41:09.760
I suppose not.

41:21.105 --> 41:23.107
Well, what is your opinion?

41:24.108 --> 41:25.859
That you're greatly to blame
for playing pranks

41:25.943 --> 41:28.112
on a man like Mr. Boldwood.

41:29.655 --> 41:31.782
Your actions were
unworthy of you.

41:32.074 --> 41:37.371
Unworthy? May I ask
where my unworthiness lies?

41:37.955 --> 41:39.957
In rejecting you, perhaps?

41:40.332 --> 41:41.834
I've long given up
thinking of that.

41:42.876 --> 41:44.670
Or wishing it, either.

41:47.297 --> 41:48.507
But I will say this.

41:48.590 --> 41:51.176
Leading on a man you
don't care for is beneath you.

41:54.054 --> 41:57.391
I cannot allow a man to
criticize my private conduct.

41:57.516 --> 41:59.393
You will please leave the farm
at the end of the week.

42:04.732 --> 42:06.150
(METAL CLANGS)

42:07.860 --> 42:09.862
I'd prefer to go at once.

42:10.195 --> 42:12.698
Then go. I never want to
see your face again.

42:14.742 --> 42:16.869
Very well, Miss Everdene.

42:23.250 --> 42:24.418
(DOOR SLAMS)

42:39.349 --> 42:40.976
(SHEEP BLEATING)

42:53.530 --> 42:56.366
Whoa, there we are.
There.

43:00.287 --> 43:01.747
What's wrong with them?

43:02.206 --> 43:03.874
They broke fence
and ate the young clover.

43:03.957 --> 43:05.167
Makes their stomachs swell.

43:05.375 --> 43:06.752
(BREATHING WEAKLY)

43:07.252 --> 43:08.420
BATHSHEBA: Well,
what do we do now?

43:08.504 --> 43:10.506
JOSEPH: Nothing.
The whole flock is blasted.

43:10.756 --> 43:12.257
You mean they're
all going to die?

43:12.341 --> 43:13.342
Most probably.

43:13.509 --> 43:14.510
Another one gone here, ma'am.

43:14.593 --> 43:16.720
Only one way
of saving them.

43:16.804 --> 43:19.556
You must pierce
their side with a tool.

43:19.932 --> 43:22.810
A hollow tube.
Pricker inside.

43:22.935 --> 43:24.686
Well, can you do it?

43:24.895 --> 43:26.105
This one's still alive.

43:26.271 --> 43:27.481
No.

43:27.606 --> 43:29.566
Can I?
Oh, good Lord, no.

43:30.109 --> 43:31.735
One inch to
the right or the left,

43:31.819 --> 43:33.821
and you kill
the ewe for sure.

43:33.946 --> 43:37.825
Not even a shepherd
can do it, as a rule.

43:38.450 --> 43:40.077
Well, who, then?

43:50.921 --> 43:52.005
(SIGHS)

43:55.926 --> 43:57.344
Gabriel!

43:58.929 --> 44:00.347
Gabriel!

44:00.472 --> 44:02.558
Gabriel Oak, wait!

44:04.101 --> 44:05.310
Miss Everdene needs you.

44:11.024 --> 44:14.653
Why are you alone?
Did you find him?

44:15.070 --> 44:16.405
Yes, miss.

44:17.364 --> 44:18.657
So what did he say?

44:20.576 --> 44:21.994
He said...

44:23.537 --> 44:24.872
<i>BATHSHEBA'. Joseph'?</i>

44:26.123 --> 44:27.207
He said you're
to go in person

44:27.291 --> 44:28.876
and request him civilly
in a proper manner.

44:30.586 --> 44:32.963
Where does he get his airs?
I'll do no such thing.

44:34.673 --> 44:36.133
He said you'd say that.

44:36.216 --> 44:39.553
He said to reply,
"Beggars can't be choosers."

44:42.890 --> 44:44.516
(HORSE APPROACHING)

45:00.240 --> 45:02.117
(PANTING) Mr. Oak.

45:04.745 --> 45:06.038
Gabriel.

45:07.956 --> 45:09.499
Gabriel.

45:11.668 --> 45:13.754
Please don't
desert me, Gabriel.

45:15.714 --> 45:17.216
I need your help.

45:37.444 --> 45:39.321
Make room for me.

46:08.225 --> 46:09.268
LIDDY: I wanna see.

46:09.351 --> 46:10.560
COGGAN: No, don't you start,
Liddy, be quiet.

46:10.686 --> 46:12.562
GABRIEL: Find the spot.

46:14.982 --> 46:16.483
Between the ribs.

46:19.194 --> 46:20.696
Oh, Lord!
No,no,no,no,no.

46:20.821 --> 46:22.489
Now...

46:22.990 --> 46:24.992
LIDDY: I can see
his heart beating.

46:25.450 --> 46:26.910
(AIR HISSING)

46:29.454 --> 46:30.622
Come on.
COGGAN: Come on, girl.

46:31.999 --> 46:33.125
GABRIEL: Come on.

46:33.208 --> 46:34.751
She'll be all right.
She'll be all right.

46:34.835 --> 46:36.253
You all right?
You all right, Pixie?

46:36.378 --> 46:37.838
Yeah, come on.
(BLEATING)

46:37.921 --> 46:39.131
All right, Pixie! Pixie!

46:39.298 --> 46:40.507
(LAUGHTER)

46:41.466 --> 46:43.051
Hey! Come here!

46:47.097 --> 46:48.932
(SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY)
(BLEATING)

46:52.060 --> 46:53.812
(COGGAN WHISTLING)

47:13.248 --> 47:15.667
<i>JOSEPH: Lay me low</i>

47:16.501 --> 47:18.754
<i>Lay me low</i>

47:19.588 --> 47:23.675
<i>Where no-one can see me</i>

47:24.676 --> 47:27.846
<i>Where no-one can find me</i>

47:28.180 --> 47:33.268
<i>Where no-one can hurt me</i>

47:33.602 --> 47:35.103
(ALL CHEERING)

47:42.277 --> 47:43.278
Get out.

47:44.446 --> 47:46.281
Please, quiet.

47:48.116 --> 47:54.956
<i>Oh, early one morning
As I was a walking</i>

47:56.375 --> 48:02.381
<i>The fields and the meadows
They looked so green and gay</i>

48:02.964 --> 48:05.967
<i>The birds sang so sweetly</i>

48:06.134 --> 48:09.513
<i>So pleasant and so charming</i>

48:09.888 --> 48:12.224
<i>So early in the morning</i>

48:12.391 --> 48:13.475
<i>At the break of day</i>

48:13.558 --> 48:16.686
Miss. Mr. Boldwood is here.

48:16.812 --> 48:19.898
Thank you. Thank you, Jan.
Jan, thank you.

48:19.981 --> 48:22.192
(APPLAUDING AND CHEERING)

48:23.402 --> 48:24.903
Mr. Boldwood.

48:24.986 --> 48:27.572
What a pleasant surprise.
Will you join us?

48:27.656 --> 48:29.825
(ALL TALKING INDISTINCTLY)

48:43.880 --> 48:45.215
Nice to have
you, sir.

48:49.010 --> 48:50.554
JACOB: A song, ma'am.

48:50.679 --> 48:52.597
I have no voice.

48:52.681 --> 48:53.807
(ALL PROTESTING)

48:53.890 --> 48:56.309
JACOB: Come on, ma'am,
you've got a lovely voice.

48:56.393 --> 48:58.562
(ALL CHEERING ENCOURAGINGLY)

49:08.363 --> 49:13.535
<i>Come all you fair
and tender girls</i>

49:14.119 --> 49:19.749
<i>That flourish in your prime</i>

49:20.083 --> 49:25.464
<i>Beware, beware
Keep your garden fair</i>

49:26.047 --> 49:31.470
<i>Let no man steal your thyme</i>

49:31.887 --> 49:37.058
<i>Let no man steal your thyme</i>

49:38.059 --> 49:43.064
<i>For when your thyme
it is past and gone</i>

49:44.065 --> 49:49.404
<i>He'll care no more for you</i>

49:50.238 --> 49:56.077
<i>And every place where
your thyme was waste</i>

49:56.161 --> 50:01.333
<i>Will all spread o'er with rue</i>

50:01.917 --> 50:06.796
<i>Will all spread o'er with rue</i>

50:08.465 --> 50:13.261
<i>The gardener's son
was standing by</i>

50:14.095 --> 50:18.350
<i>Three flowers he gave to me</i>

50:20.101 --> 50:25.357
<i>The pink, the blue
and the violet true</i>

50:26.024 --> 50:31.279
<i>And the red, red rosy tree</i>

50:31.947 --> 50:36.618
<i>And the red, red rosy tree</i>

50:37.953 --> 50:43.166
<i>But I refused
the red rose bush</i>

50:44.125 --> 50:49.130
<i>And gained the willow tree</i>

50:50.006 --> 50:55.303
<i>That all the world
may plainly see</i>

50:56.388 --> 51:01.184
<i>How my love slighted me</i>

51:02.310 --> 51:08.233
<i>How my love slighted me</i>

51:08.984 --> 51:11.403
(ALL APPLAUDING)

51:13.154 --> 51:15.323
I thought we were
rather good together.

51:15.407 --> 51:16.658
So did I.

51:16.825 --> 51:19.661
We would make
a fine duo.

51:19.828 --> 51:21.705
I wanted to thank you
for not approaching me

51:21.830 --> 51:23.665
on that subject again.

51:25.500 --> 51:28.003
Well, it has
not been easy.

51:36.511 --> 51:38.513
Do you wish me to, er,

51:38.597 --> 51:40.348
accompany you back
to the house?

51:41.516 --> 51:43.435
No, I like to walk around
the farm every night

51:43.518 --> 51:45.228
to make sure all is safe.

51:46.438 --> 51:49.691
Then I...
I can walk with you.

51:50.066 --> 51:52.068
I've done it
many times alone.

51:53.194 --> 51:54.696
Good night,
Mr. Boldwood.

51:54.779 --> 51:57.449
You've been very kind.
A pleasure to see you.

52:31.399 --> 52:32.734
(GASPS)

52:32.901 --> 52:34.486
Who are you?

52:34.653 --> 52:36.279
I'm sorry.
I seem to be lost.

52:36.780 --> 52:39.449
We're entangled.
Are you hurt?

52:39.783 --> 52:40.909
No.

52:41.076 --> 52:42.077
I'm looking
for Weatherbury.

52:42.243 --> 52:43.370
I hope I didn't
startle you.

52:43.453 --> 52:45.580
We've got hitched
together somehow.

52:45.664 --> 52:47.165
Here, allow me.

52:47.248 --> 52:49.751
No. No. Please,
let me do it myself.

52:51.503 --> 52:53.963
If you lift your
foot for a moment.

53:08.144 --> 53:09.646
Please don't stare.

53:09.771 --> 53:12.482
I don't think I've ever seen
a face as beautiful as yours.

53:12.941 --> 53:14.192
(FABRIC RIPS)

53:16.945 --> 53:20.782
You shouldn't be here.
Please let me have the lamp.

53:31.209 --> 53:34.337
FARMHAND: A mighty impressive
harvest this looks like.

53:38.299 --> 53:40.802
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

53:46.057 --> 53:47.142
LIDDYI Miss,

53:48.059 --> 53:49.519
look.

53:53.481 --> 53:54.983
Who is he, Liddy?

53:55.150 --> 53:57.318
Sergeant Francis Troy.

53:57.402 --> 54:00.530
Noble blood,
full of promise.
Very sharp and trim.

54:01.823 --> 54:02.782
Well-educated.

54:02.866 --> 54:04.659
There was good things
expected of him.

54:05.160 --> 54:07.829
He threw it all in
to be a soldier.

54:09.414 --> 54:10.874
Well, I won't have it.

54:11.040 --> 54:12.542
What are you doing, miss?

54:12.667 --> 54:14.878
I'm going to
tell him to leave.

54:20.008 --> 54:21.301
Sergeant Troy,

54:21.384 --> 54:23.928
I must absolutely insist that
you leave at this very moment.

54:24.012 --> 54:25.513
I can't.

54:25.680 --> 54:27.515
Will you follow me, please?

54:29.434 --> 54:30.685
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

54:48.119 --> 54:49.704
What angers you, exactly?

54:50.872 --> 54:51.831
Please.

54:51.915 --> 54:53.875
What I said
or the way I said it?

54:54.042 --> 54:55.585
You must know.

54:56.085 --> 54:57.170
There must be some man

54:57.253 --> 54:58.463
who tells you
that you're beautiful.

54:58.880 --> 55:00.840
Oh, not to my face, not...

55:00.924 --> 55:02.675
But there is someone
who kisses you?

55:02.759 --> 55:03.927
I've never been kissed.

55:10.600 --> 55:13.770
Why couldn't you have just
passed by and said nothing?

55:15.313 --> 55:16.481
Do you forgive me?

55:18.900 --> 55:20.568
I do not.
Why?

55:20.735 --> 55:23.196
Because the things you say...

55:23.279 --> 55:25.156
I said that
you were beautiful.

55:30.078 --> 55:32.413
I wonder if you fight
as well as you speak.

55:32.497 --> 55:33.790
Better.

55:39.504 --> 55:43.007
Meet me. Tomorrow.

55:44.425 --> 55:46.135
I can't.

55:46.302 --> 55:47.512
You don't want to?

55:47.679 --> 55:48.930
Yes, but...

55:49.013 --> 55:50.431
Then you must.
I mustn't.

55:50.765 --> 55:52.475
(WHISPERS) Nobody would know.

55:55.186 --> 55:56.855
Please go now.

55:57.772 --> 55:59.107
Tomorrow.

55:59.774 --> 56:01.109
8200.

56:02.318 --> 56:04.320
The hollow in the ferns.

56:13.621 --> 56:14.956
(SIGHS)

56:16.040 --> 56:17.667
(POCKET WATCH TICKING)

58:04.565 --> 58:05.566
Do you trust me?

58:07.235 --> 58:08.319
I do.

58:14.325 --> 58:16.077
I give you my word
as a soldier,

58:16.160 --> 58:17.954
I will not harm you.

58:18.079 --> 58:20.081
The sword is blunt,

58:20.581 --> 58:23.418
but you must not flinch.

58:24.002 --> 58:26.087
I'll try not to.

58:58.995 --> 59:00.163
(GRUNTS)

59:11.799 --> 59:13.676
You cut my hair.

59:16.387 --> 59:18.306
This sword could
skin you alive.

59:18.848 --> 59:21.309
But you told me I was safe.

59:21.476 --> 59:23.895
And you were.
Entirely safe.

59:24.520 --> 59:26.647
I gave you my word.

59:28.357 --> 59:30.485
Now I will take this.

59:39.368 --> 59:40.995
(BATHSHEBA MOANING)

01:00:48.437 --> 01:00:49.939
Miss Everdene.

01:00:51.399 --> 01:00:53.151
Perhaps I could
walk with you?

01:00:53.276 --> 01:00:55.778
I'm quite happy
to walk by myself.

01:00:57.738 --> 01:01:00.116
You should have nothing
to do with him.

01:01:00.449 --> 01:01:02.451
He's not good
enough for you.

01:01:02.952 --> 01:01:05.079
He's a perfectly
decent man.

01:01:06.289 --> 01:01:07.582
That's not
what I believe.

01:01:07.665 --> 01:01:10.251
Why? What have you heard?

01:01:11.627 --> 01:01:15.089
You don't know him at all.
It's all rumors.

01:01:15.506 --> 01:01:17.008
Prejudice simply because
he's a soldier.

01:01:17.091 --> 01:01:19.594
I like soldiers.
But not this one.

01:01:19.677 --> 01:01:22.096
I believe him to have
no conscience at all.

01:01:23.139 --> 01:01:25.516
Stay clear.
Don't listen to him.

01:01:25.600 --> 01:01:27.268
Don't believe him.

01:01:27.643 --> 01:01:28.936
Get rid of him.

01:01:29.353 --> 01:01:31.147
And what is it to you?

01:01:34.275 --> 01:01:35.860
I'm not such a fool
as to imagine

01:01:35.943 --> 01:01:38.905
I might stand a chance now
that you are so above me.

01:01:38.988 --> 01:01:42.825
But don't suppose I'm content
to stay a nobody all my life.

01:01:43.326 --> 01:01:45.953
One day I will leave you.
You can be sure of that.

01:01:46.495 --> 01:01:48.623
But for now,
I care for you too much

01:01:48.706 --> 01:01:51.042
to see you go to ruin
because of him.

01:01:53.002 --> 01:01:55.838
So if you don't mind, I'll...

01:01:57.798 --> 01:01:59.967
I'll stay by your side.

01:02:02.136 --> 01:02:04.138
Good evening.

01:02:21.989 --> 01:02:24.075
BATH S H E BA: Mr. BOIdWOOd,

01:02:24.158 --> 01:02:27.119
<i>you have been a dear friend
to me these past months.</i>

01:02:27.203 --> 01:02:29.455
<i>And it is because
I value our friendship</i>

01:02:29.538 --> 01:02:31.999
<i>so greatly that I am writing.</i>

01:02:32.708 --> 01:02:35.711
<i>I am honored by your proposal</i>

01:02:35.836 --> 01:02:38.005
<i>and have given it
much thought,</i>

01:02:38.089 --> 01:02:40.466
<i>but I must tell you that,
to my own surprise,</i>

01:02:40.549 --> 01:02:42.760
<i>I have undergone
what can only be described</i>

01:02:42.843 --> 01:02:45.179
<i>as a change of heart</i>

01:02:45.263 --> 01:02:48.015
<i>and I'm afraid
I cannot accept your offer.</i>

01:03:11.247 --> 01:03:13.749
I wasn't sure you'd be here.

01:03:14.083 --> 01:03:16.252
Where else would I be?

01:03:18.713 --> 01:03:20.381
You ready?

01:03:22.883 --> 01:03:24.719
Are you sure?

01:03:29.056 --> 01:03:31.225
How does this sound?

01:03:32.310 --> 01:03:35.062
Mrs. Bathsheba Troy.

01:03:35.146 --> 01:03:37.315
(CHURCH BELL TOLLING)

01:03:50.786 --> 01:03:52.121
(WHISPERS) All right?

01:04:48.469 --> 01:04:50.137
Walk on.

01:05:28.717 --> 01:05:30.511
(WIND HOWLING)

01:05:31.554 --> 01:05:32.596
(BARN DOOR SLAMS)

01:05:43.899 --> 01:05:45.276
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

01:05:52.032 --> 01:05:54.326
(BAND PLAYING
UPBEAT FOLK MUSIC)

01:06:22.438 --> 01:06:23.981
(LAUGHING)

01:06:31.864 --> 01:06:33.365
(some ENDS)

01:06:33.449 --> 01:06:35.159
(ALL APPLAUDING AND CHEERING)

01:06:37.870 --> 01:06:40.956
FRANCIS: Gentlemen.
Ladies and gentlemen.

01:06:42.625 --> 01:06:47.004
A short time ago,
I had the privilege

01:06:47.963 --> 01:06:52.885
and the simple fortune
of meeting this angel.

01:06:53.761 --> 01:06:55.221
Your mistress.

01:06:56.055 --> 01:06:59.225
And now I stand before
you her husband,

01:07:00.267 --> 01:07:01.602
your master,

01:07:02.811 --> 01:07:05.523
and the proudest man
you will ever see.

01:07:05.981 --> 01:07:10.069
So, please,
charge your glasses

01:07:10.152 --> 01:07:15.074
and sing out to
my most beautiful wife,

01:07:15.699 --> 01:07:19.411
Mrs. Bathsheba Troy.

01:07:20.079 --> 01:07:22.915
(ALL CHEERING)

01:07:25.292 --> 01:07:28.504
Miss Everdene,
there's going to be a storm.

01:07:28.629 --> 01:07:32.424
Oak, you big lump.
To me.

01:07:32.508 --> 01:07:34.426
There's going to be a storm.

01:07:34.510 --> 01:07:37.680
We need to protect the ricks
or we'll lose the harvest.

01:07:38.347 --> 01:07:40.683
I need five to six men
for an hour, no more.

01:07:40.808 --> 01:07:42.476
Frank, perhaps
we ought to...
No.

01:07:42.560 --> 01:07:44.186
Darling, it's our
wedding celebration.

01:07:45.354 --> 01:07:49.650
It will not rain tonight.
My wife forbids it.

01:07:50.359 --> 01:07:52.319
Now if you'll excuse me.

01:07:53.320 --> 01:07:55.155
Ffiends!

01:07:56.031 --> 01:07:57.032
One more thing.

01:07:58.409 --> 01:08:02.997
I may no longer
be Sergeant Troy,

01:08:03.122 --> 01:08:07.084
but I remain a soldier
in this one respect!

01:08:07.167 --> 01:08:08.252
(ALL CHEERING)

01:08:08.335 --> 01:08:12.006
The finest bottles
of French brandy,

01:08:13.007 --> 01:08:16.176
a triple-strength dose
for every man.

01:08:16.301 --> 01:08:17.469
Cheers! To your health!

01:08:17.636 --> 01:08:18.804
(ALL CHEERING)

01:08:18.886 --> 01:08:20.471
(MUSIC RESUMES)

01:08:23.600 --> 01:08:24.935
(INAUDIBLE)

01:08:30.983 --> 01:08:32.443
(WIND HOWLING)

01:08:46.540 --> 01:08:47.916
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

01:08:52.962 --> 01:08:54.673
(ALL CHEERING)

01:08:58.176 --> 01:09:03.015
<i>"Pretty Polly, Pretty Polly
It's I've come a-wooin"'</i>

01:09:03.599 --> 01:09:08.729
<i>"Pretty Polly, Pretty Polly
It's I've come a-wooin"'</i>

01:09:10.064 --> 01:09:12.733
<i>She says, "Creep and crawl
through the window, then</i>

01:09:12.941 --> 01:09:14.693
<i>"And let's get doin'</i>

01:09:14.777 --> 01:09:19.323
<i>"And lay your leg over me
Over me, do</i>

01:09:19.990 --> 01:09:25.203
<i>"Oh, me britches is tight
and I cannot undo 'em</i>

01:09:25.328 --> 01:09:30.501
<i>"Oh, me britches is tight
and I cannot undo 'em</i>

01:09:30.626 --> 01:09:32.836
<i>"There's a knife
on the windowsill</i>

01:09:32.920 --> 01:09:34.421
<i>"Love, take it to 'em</i>

01:09:35.005 --> 01:09:37.633
<i>"And lay your leg over me..."</i>

01:09:37.925 --> 01:09:39.718
(WIND HOWLING)
(GABRIEL PANTING)

01:09:56.985 --> 01:10:01.699
<i>About 40 weeks after,
the fine baby come bawlin'</i>

01:10:02.825 --> 01:10:07.287
<i>Never regretted
that creepin' and crawlin'</i>

01:10:07.371 --> 01:10:10.499
<i>"Lay your leg over me
Over me..."</i>

01:10:10.666 --> 01:10:11.959
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

01:10:41.822 --> 01:10:43.615
(RUMBLING CONTINUES)

01:10:58.464 --> 01:10:59.840
BATHSHEBAI Gabriel!

01:11:02.509 --> 01:11:03.510
Gabriel!

01:11:05.763 --> 01:11:06.930
What can I do?

01:11:07.055 --> 01:11:08.932
It's too dangerous!

01:11:09.016 --> 01:11:10.559
I'm coming up!

01:11:20.819 --> 01:11:21.945
Hold it down.

01:11:23.197 --> 01:11:25.073
Still no rain.

01:11:25.491 --> 01:11:27.201
It'll come.

01:11:38.670 --> 01:11:39.713
(THUNDER CRASHES)

01:11:39.880 --> 01:11:40.923
(YELPS)

01:11:41.006 --> 01:11:45.135
Come on, hold me!
Come here. Come here.

01:11:45.260 --> 01:11:46.970
(BOTH PANTING)

01:11:50.808 --> 01:11:52.893
Come here. Come on.

01:11:53.185 --> 01:11:54.728
(BOTH LAUGHING)

01:12:13.580 --> 01:12:15.666
Gabriel, I've been a fool.

01:12:16.333 --> 01:12:19.837
I've always had contempt
for silly girls

01:12:19.962 --> 01:12:23.257
dazzled by flattery
in a scarlet uniform and...

01:12:23.590 --> 01:12:26.468
And now I've done
what I swore I would never do.

01:12:28.720 --> 01:12:31.139
But he told me
about another woman,

01:12:31.932 --> 01:12:34.309
a woman more beautiful
that he'd loved before,

01:12:34.393 --> 01:12:36.270
and I couldn't bear it.

01:12:38.188 --> 01:12:40.023
So somewhere between
jealousy and distraction,

01:12:40.107 --> 01:12:41.233
I married him.

01:12:41.775 --> 01:12:44.653
I don't want an opinion
on the subject, I just...

01:12:45.195 --> 01:12:47.114
In fact, I forbid it.

01:12:52.536 --> 01:12:53.871
Go to bed.

01:12:55.122 --> 01:12:57.499
I'll finish it
on my own.

01:12:58.500 --> 01:13:00.168
Gabriel...

01:13:03.755 --> 01:13:05.382
Thank you.

01:13:30.532 --> 01:13:31.658
GABRIEL: Sir?

01:13:35.996 --> 01:13:37.205
Mr. Boldwood, sir!

01:13:38.081 --> 01:13:41.126
I wanted to ensure your
mistress' crops were safe.

01:13:41.460 --> 01:13:44.212
Good work, Gabriel.
She's lucky to have you.

01:13:45.464 --> 01:13:47.174
Wait a moment, sir.

01:13:55.265 --> 01:13:56.558
You seem unwell, sir.

01:13:57.434 --> 01:13:59.019
You should go home.

01:14:00.938 --> 01:14:01.939
Yes.

01:14:04.900 --> 01:14:06.860
Yes, I will.

01:14:12.157 --> 01:14:13.492
Oak.

01:14:15.494 --> 01:14:18.705
You know that things have
not gone well with me, lately.

01:14:20.290 --> 01:14:24.294
I was going to get a little
settled in life. But, er...

01:14:28.340 --> 01:14:30.342
it was not to be.

01:14:31.468 --> 01:14:32.803
(CHUCKLES)

01:14:33.303 --> 01:14:35.597
I daresay
I'm something of a...

01:14:36.431 --> 01:14:38.600
A joke about the parish.

01:14:39.476 --> 01:14:42.980
But I do wanna make
one thing clear.

01:14:43.522 --> 01:14:46.525
There was no jilting
on her part.

01:14:47.567 --> 01:14:52.239
We were never engaged.
No matter what people say.

01:14:53.907 --> 01:14:55.742
She promised me nothing.

01:15:01.373 --> 01:15:03.250
And yet,

01:15:03.875 --> 01:15:05.335
Gabriel,

01:15:08.463 --> 01:15:12.134
I feel the most
terrible grief.

01:15:18.765 --> 01:15:20.892
Not a word to her.

01:15:22.019 --> 01:15:24.604
We understand
each other, yes?

01:15:26.732 --> 01:15:27.733
Yes, sir.

01:16:18.742 --> 01:16:19.743
(CROWD GROANING)

01:16:19.910 --> 01:16:20.952
Damn and bother!

01:16:24.372 --> 01:16:25.874
Sit.

01:16:26.124 --> 01:16:28.418
Stay. Now, turn around.

01:16:34.591 --> 01:16:35.801
Can you spare
a coin, please?

01:16:35.967 --> 01:16:37.177
No, no.

01:16:37.886 --> 01:16:39.429
(BOTH GRUNTING)

01:16:39.513 --> 01:16:40.722
(CROWD SHOUTING)

01:16:41.306 --> 01:16:42.641
FRANCIS: Hit him!

01:16:43.183 --> 01:16:44.184
Come on!

01:16:45.685 --> 01:16:47.270
WOMAN: Knock him out!

01:16:48.605 --> 01:16:50.190
MAN: Hit him!

01:16:51.441 --> 01:16:52.901
(ALL CHEERING)

01:16:54.903 --> 01:16:57.280
Pay up.
Pay up, Mr. Troy.

01:16:58.115 --> 01:16:59.783
Just take it.

01:17:05.497 --> 01:17:06.581
FANNY: Sir, excuse me.

01:17:06.665 --> 01:17:08.291
Could you spare
a coin, please?

01:17:08.792 --> 01:17:10.210
No.

01:17:12.796 --> 01:17:13.964
Fanny?

01:17:21.847 --> 01:17:23.140
Hello, Frank.

01:17:25.475 --> 01:17:26.810
Hello.

01:17:29.229 --> 01:17:30.522
You're so pale.

01:17:31.189 --> 01:17:32.482
Oh, Frank.

01:17:32.566 --> 01:17:34.693
Darling,
your hands are shaking.

01:17:35.235 --> 01:17:38.196
I thought you said
All Souls, not All Saints.

01:17:38.280 --> 01:17:40.282
I went to the wrong church.

01:17:41.408 --> 01:17:45.370
When I got there, you'd gone.
And I don't blame you,

01:17:45.453 --> 01:17:47.873
but it's been very hard,
Frank. I...

01:17:47.956 --> 01:17:49.249
Not now.

01:17:50.458 --> 01:17:52.752
My wife mustn't see you.

01:17:53.378 --> 01:17:54.796
Your wife?

01:18:03.263 --> 01:18:04.598
(GASPS)

01:18:05.557 --> 01:18:07.893
Mrs. Troy is very beautiful.

01:18:09.644 --> 01:18:11.313
No more than you.

01:18:11.396 --> 01:18:12.647
(FANNY SOBBING)

01:18:13.940 --> 01:18:18.445
Frank, I must tell you,
I'm carrying your child.

01:18:18.653 --> 01:18:20.030
What?

01:18:32.292 --> 01:18:35.378
What if I told you that
I'd made a terrible mistake,

01:18:36.922 --> 01:18:39.174
but that I will make amends?

01:18:40.217 --> 01:18:41.551
I swear on my life

01:18:41.635 --> 01:18:44.512
I will find a home
for you and our baby.

01:18:44.930 --> 01:18:46.806
You've sworn before, Frank.

01:18:46.973 --> 01:18:48.808
No, this time... This time...

01:18:56.441 --> 01:18:59.069
Go to Budmouth.
Stay at the Union.

01:18:59.152 --> 01:19:01.029
The workhouse, Frank?

01:19:01.112 --> 01:19:02.948
Tonight, just tonight.
One night.

01:19:03.031 --> 01:19:05.867
And then meet me tomorrow
at 10:00 on the bridge.

01:19:06.326 --> 01:19:08.370
I'll bring you
all the money I have

01:19:08.453 --> 01:19:09.871
and I'll find
a home for you.

01:19:10.163 --> 01:19:12.040
You'll be safe, my darling.

01:19:12.123 --> 01:19:15.543
And I promise you,
I promise you

01:19:15.669 --> 01:19:17.712
I will make amends.

01:19:23.009 --> 01:19:24.719
Get back in the carriage.

01:19:25.053 --> 01:19:26.930
Do you know
who that woman is?

01:19:27.264 --> 01:19:28.431
I do.

01:19:28.682 --> 01:19:29.849
Who is she?

01:19:30.016 --> 01:19:31.142
She's nothing.

01:19:32.352 --> 01:19:34.396
Get back in the carriage.

01:19:35.355 --> 01:19:36.690
Frank...

01:20:06.303 --> 01:20:08.680
(PANTING)

01:20:35.123 --> 01:20:36.333
(GROANING)

01:20:45.925 --> 01:20:48.553
Could you let me
have £20?

01:20:51.139 --> 01:20:52.640
What for?

01:20:53.350 --> 01:20:54.893
Ineedit

01:20:57.103 --> 01:21:00.023
If you continue to gamble,
we will lose the farm.

01:21:00.148 --> 01:21:01.232
It's not for gambling.

01:21:01.399 --> 01:21:02.484
What's it for?

01:21:02.609 --> 01:21:03.693
Why should it matter
what it's for?

01:21:03.777 --> 01:21:05.111
It's my money.

01:21:05.570 --> 01:21:07.697
I work for it,
don't I?

01:21:07.781 --> 01:21:10.367
No. You don't.

01:21:11.117 --> 01:21:13.286
Not proper farm work.

01:21:15.163 --> 01:21:17.582
Don't do something
you'll regret.

01:21:19.876 --> 01:21:23.505
The money is required
for farm expenses.

01:21:42.065 --> 01:21:43.775
(HORSE APPROACHING)

01:22:10.427 --> 01:22:12.011
UNDERTAKER:
No mistake, Mr. Oak.

01:22:12.095 --> 01:22:14.764
This was Miss Robbin's
last known abode.

01:22:14.848 --> 01:22:16.015
BATHSHEBA: Fanny was
my uncle's servant

01:22:16.099 --> 01:22:17.809
and we shall treat
her with respect.

01:22:18.768 --> 01:22:20.854
Perhaps we should
take her to the church,

01:22:20.937 --> 01:22:22.439
just for tonight.

01:22:22.522 --> 01:22:24.858
No, bring her inside, please.

01:22:45.420 --> 01:22:47.172
What did she die of, Liddy?

01:22:48.923 --> 01:22:50.633
I don't know, miss.

01:22:52.844 --> 01:22:54.512
There were rumors, but...

01:22:55.346 --> 01:22:57.974
Fanny had a sweetheart,
didn't she?

01:22:58.475 --> 01:23:00.059
Yes, miss.

01:23:01.394 --> 01:23:03.313
A soldier.

01:23:07.317 --> 01:23:10.153
LIDDY: Please, come
and sit upstairs with me.

01:23:27.253 --> 01:23:30.423
I seem to cry
a great deal these days.

01:23:33.009 --> 01:23:34.552
I never used to cry at all.

01:23:45.146 --> 01:23:46.147
Good night, Liddy.

01:23:47.190 --> 01:23:49.067
'Night, miss.

01:23:58.785 --> 01:24:00.078
(DOOR CLOSES)

01:24:37.198 --> 01:24:38.408
(GASPS)

01:24:45.039 --> 01:24:46.457
What?

01:24:47.041 --> 01:24:48.167
Who is it?

01:24:48.251 --> 01:24:49.669
I can't say...

01:24:49.836 --> 01:24:51.296
Stay, stay. stay-

01:25:11.316 --> 01:25:13.318
Don't kiss them, Frank.

01:25:13.651 --> 01:25:16.070
I'm still your wife.

01:25:23.745 --> 01:25:26.539
This woman,
dead as she is,

01:25:26.623 --> 01:25:32.545
is more to me than you
ever were, or are, or can be.

01:25:35.048 --> 01:25:37.133
You are nothing to me now.

01:25:39.552 --> 01:25:41.346
Nothing.

01:27:28.995 --> 01:27:31.372
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

01:27:48.931 --> 01:27:50.933
CONSTABLE: Mrs. Troy?

01:27:54.437 --> 01:27:56.481
I'm afraid...

01:27:56.564 --> 01:27:58.983
I'm afraid your
husband has drowned.

01:29:21.357 --> 01:29:22.900
(EXHALING)

01:29:32.994 --> 01:29:34.078
GABRIEL: That's a great
responsibility, sir.

01:29:34.161 --> 01:29:35.162
Nonsense.

01:29:35.246 --> 01:29:36.581
No reason why a man
of your ability

01:29:36.664 --> 01:29:39.208
shouldn't be able to
superintend two farms.

01:29:39.333 --> 01:29:40.543
And why shouldn't there
be stronger links

01:29:40.626 --> 01:29:42.253
between our establishments?

01:29:42.336 --> 01:29:46.048
Think of it. Two thousand
acres under your sole charge.

01:29:46.257 --> 01:29:48.134
A share of my profits.

01:29:48.259 --> 01:29:49.343
Miss Everdene
needs me here.

01:29:49.427 --> 01:29:50.845
And her farm
will have priority.

01:29:50.928 --> 01:29:52.305
I'd still need
Miss Everdene's permission.

01:29:52.388 --> 01:29:53.472
But, of course.

01:29:53.556 --> 01:29:54.724
Of course, I wouldn't
dare do anything

01:29:54.807 --> 01:29:56.517
without her blessing. And,

01:29:56.642 --> 01:29:59.186
if it'll help
sway your decision,

01:30:03.441 --> 01:30:05.943
there's an old comrade
of yours here.

01:30:07.904 --> 01:30:08.905
GABRIEL: Georgie!

01:30:09.071 --> 01:30:10.239
Had to go all the way
to Norcombe Hill

01:30:10.323 --> 01:30:11.365
to find this old fella.

01:30:11.616 --> 01:30:12.700
You pleased?

01:30:13.075 --> 01:30:14.744
Yes, sir, very much.

01:30:14.869 --> 01:30:17.705
And I'll have your
decision soon, yes?

01:30:18.164 --> 01:30:19.665
You will, sir.

01:30:19.916 --> 01:30:21.709
Hey, Georgie.

01:30:23.794 --> 01:30:24.795
Come on. Come on.

01:30:24.921 --> 01:30:25.922
(BARKING PLAYFULLY)

01:30:36.140 --> 01:30:37.600
Come on! Come on!

01:30:39.435 --> 01:30:41.896
BATHSHEBA: Gabriel, you're
getting on in the world.

01:30:42.480 --> 01:30:44.607
Of course you must
accept the offer.

01:30:44.690 --> 01:30:46.817
GABRIEL: Only with
your approval.

01:30:47.151 --> 01:30:48.945
If I lose the farm,
there may be no future

01:30:49.028 --> 01:30:51.072
for any of us here.

01:30:51.530 --> 01:30:53.741
You know where
my loyalty lies.

01:30:56.285 --> 01:30:58.329
You're a man of great talent.

01:30:58.663 --> 01:30:59.997
It's only natural
that you should rise.

01:31:00.081 --> 01:31:02.291
I've no desire
to hold you back.

01:31:04.919 --> 01:31:06.420
(HORSE NEIGHING)

01:31:13.386 --> 01:31:14.512
Thank you.

01:31:19.892 --> 01:31:21.978
Come on, Georgie.
Come on.

01:31:26.065 --> 01:31:31.278
WILLIAM: Forgive me.
I understand there are debts.

01:31:32.697 --> 01:31:34.323
Your late husband.

01:31:35.491 --> 01:31:38.202
Perhaps... Perhaps we should
change the subject.

01:31:38.285 --> 01:31:39.954
Perhaps I can help.

01:31:44.417 --> 01:31:47.211
Mr. Boldwood,
that's a very kind offer,

01:31:47.294 --> 01:31:49.839
but I would never dream
of accepting any money.

01:31:54.218 --> 01:31:56.470
I am a middle-aged man

01:31:58.014 --> 01:32:01.308
willing to protect you
for the rest of your life.

01:32:03.644 --> 01:32:07.481
You may run your farm,
if you wish. Without risk.

01:32:09.734 --> 01:32:11.318
I'll pay your

01:32:12.403 --> 01:32:14.488
departed husband's debts

01:32:14.572 --> 01:32:16.741
and guarantee
its financial stability.

01:32:18.117 --> 01:32:20.327
It can be your pastime.

01:32:22.580 --> 01:32:25.249
Of course, we'd need to wait,

01:32:25.750 --> 01:32:27.793
for propriety's sake.

01:32:28.502 --> 01:32:30.254
But when you're ready,

01:32:31.088 --> 01:32:33.174
I'm offering you shelter.

01:32:34.216 --> 01:32:38.220
Comfort. A safe harbor.

01:32:41.307 --> 01:32:43.059
As my wife.

01:32:47.605 --> 01:32:49.857
You must at least admire
my persistence.

01:32:49.940 --> 01:32:51.317
(LAUGHS)

01:32:53.069 --> 01:32:54.278
I do.

01:32:54.361 --> 01:32:55.362
And like me?

01:32:55.446 --> 01:32:56.489
Yes.

01:32:57.698 --> 01:33:00.117
And respect me?

01:33:00.201 --> 01:33:02.161
Yes. Very much.

01:33:02.244 --> 01:33:04.538
Which is it? Like or respect?

01:33:08.125 --> 01:33:11.212
It is difficult for a woman
to define her feelings

01:33:11.295 --> 01:33:13.923
in a language chiefly
made by men to express theirs.

01:33:14.048 --> 01:33:16.884
If you worry about a lack
of passion on your part,

01:33:16.967 --> 01:33:18.552
a lack of, er,

01:33:21.180 --> 01:33:22.681
<i>desks,</i>

01:33:23.641 --> 01:33:26.227
if you worry about marrying me

01:33:26.310 --> 01:33:29.230
merely out of guilt,

01:33:29.563 --> 01:33:31.148
and,en

01:33:32.149 --> 01:33:36.320
pity and compromise, well...

01:33:37.571 --> 01:33:39.198
I don't mind.

01:33:43.410 --> 01:33:45.162
GABRIEL: When must you
give your answer?

01:33:45.287 --> 01:33:46.872
By Christmas.

01:33:48.707 --> 01:33:50.543
It's a terrible
responsibility.

01:33:53.170 --> 01:33:55.631
I hold that man's
future in my hands.

01:33:56.257 --> 01:33:58.384
His sanity, too, perhaps.

01:33:58.467 --> 01:33:59.760
Could you care for him?

01:33:59.844 --> 01:34:02.179
BATHSHEBA: You may suppose
love is wanting.

01:34:04.056 --> 01:34:07.101
But love's a worn-out,
miserable thing for me now.

01:34:07.184 --> 01:34:09.228
GABRIEL: Why are you
asking me?

01:34:13.649 --> 01:34:16.277
I need someone
who's objective.

01:34:16.360 --> 01:34:17.945
Indifferent.
(GABRIEL CHUCKLES)

01:34:19.446 --> 01:34:22.241
Then I'm afraid you're
asking the wrong man.

01:34:40.593 --> 01:34:42.178
Good evening, Mr. Oak.

01:34:43.888 --> 01:34:45.347
GABRIEL: Good evening.

01:35:03.741 --> 01:35:04.825
WORKMAN 13 That's it.

01:35:04.992 --> 01:35:06.035
WORKMAN 21 Mind.

01:35:13.042 --> 01:35:16.003
(ORGAN PLAYING)

01:35:16.295 --> 01:35:19.006
<i>Rejoice</i>

01:35:19.089 --> 01:35:21.800
<i>Rejoice</i>

01:35:21.884 --> 01:35:25.888
<i>Emmanuel</i>

01:35:25.971 --> 01:35:28.766
<i>Shall come to thee</i>

01:35:28.849 --> 01:35:33.771
<i>O Israel</i>

01:35:36.899 --> 01:35:40.903
<i>O come, Thou Rod of Jesse...</i>

01:35:41.654 --> 01:35:44.031
WILLIAM: I appreciate you
coming along, Oak.

01:35:44.114 --> 01:35:45.115
Ah!

01:35:45.282 --> 01:35:47.576
Yes, very good.
Well done. Erm...

01:35:47.660 --> 01:35:48.702
Just more... More things.

01:35:48.869 --> 01:35:49.870
Yes, sir.

01:35:52.998 --> 01:35:54.041
(SIGHS)

01:35:54.124 --> 01:35:57.253
So what do you think?

01:35:57.878 --> 01:36:00.547
I'm not in the habit of
organizing parties.

01:36:00.798 --> 01:36:03.259
Perhaps we should make it
an annual event.

01:36:03.342 --> 01:36:04.468
Every Christmas Eve.

01:36:05.010 --> 01:36:06.553
Pveinvfled
the whole village.

01:36:06.637 --> 01:36:07.721
Do you think they'll come?

01:36:07.805 --> 01:36:09.807
Do you think
Miss Everdene will come?

01:36:09.890 --> 01:36:11.433
I'm sure she will.

01:36:12.726 --> 01:36:13.727
Yes.

01:36:14.478 --> 01:36:16.480
And you'll come
too,lhope.

01:36:17.606 --> 01:36:20.192
I know Miss Everdene
would like you to be here.

01:36:20.276 --> 01:36:21.694
Perhaps, for
an hour or so.

01:36:23.779 --> 01:36:25.364
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)

01:36:26.699 --> 01:36:30.202
Look, I'm shaking.
I'm so nervous.

01:36:31.203 --> 01:36:33.330
Gabriel, will you...

01:36:33.706 --> 01:36:34.999
As well as you can, please.

01:36:35.165 --> 01:36:36.500
<i>I'll</i> try.

01:36:36.583 --> 01:36:39.586
Is there a knot that's
particularly fashionable?

01:36:39.670 --> 01:36:40.796
(GABRIEL LAUGHING)

01:36:41.588 --> 01:36:43.716
You're asking the wrong man.

01:36:45.301 --> 01:36:46.719
What about women?

01:36:47.636 --> 01:36:49.805
Does a woman keep her promise?

01:36:51.056 --> 01:36:52.683
She has promised?

01:36:53.434 --> 01:36:55.436
An implied promise.

01:36:57.313 --> 01:36:58.689
Once again, I'm...

01:36:58.856 --> 01:37:00.232
Will she do what's right?

01:37:02.901 --> 01:37:04.820
If it's not
inconvenient to her.

01:37:05.863 --> 01:37:08.157
Oak, you've become
quite cynical lately.

01:37:09.158 --> 01:37:10.909
She never promised
that first time.

01:37:10.993 --> 01:37:14.371
Therefore, she has
never broken her promise.

01:37:14.872 --> 01:37:17.207
She hasn't promised
this time, either.

01:37:18.167 --> 01:37:21.503
But she will. Tonight.

01:37:22.004 --> 01:37:23.505
I know she will.

01:37:25.466 --> 01:37:26.967
And when she does...

01:37:32.806 --> 01:37:36.560
I wanted to tell you
in advance, Gabriel,

01:37:38.103 --> 01:37:41.106
becauselH.lbeHeve
I know your secret.

01:37:44.276 --> 01:37:46.862
I've seen you together.

01:37:48.322 --> 01:37:50.407
The way you speak to her.

01:37:51.533 --> 01:37:53.118
And watch her.

01:37:54.703 --> 01:37:56.830
And look after her.

01:37:57.164 --> 01:37:59.458
And I know her, er,

01:38:00.918 --> 01:38:04.421
profound affection for you.

01:38:05.005 --> 01:38:07.257
You've behaved like a man,

01:38:08.092 --> 01:38:09.510
and as the successful rival,

01:38:09.593 --> 01:38:12.679
successful through
your kindness,

01:38:12.763 --> 01:38:13.764
I wish to tell you

01:38:16.225 --> 01:38:18.560
lam profoundly grateful.

01:38:21.480 --> 01:38:22.898
(CHUCKLES SOFTLY)
(BUTLER CLEARS THROAT)

01:38:22.981 --> 01:38:25.567
The cook would like
a word, sir.

01:38:52.761 --> 01:38:54.847
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

01:38:54.930 --> 01:38:57.516
(LIVELY CHRISTMAS
MUSIC PLAYING)

01:39:33.802 --> 01:39:35.762
LIDDY: Kiss me. Joseph.

01:39:35.846 --> 01:39:37.848
JOSEPH: No, please don't.
Liddy, don't.

01:39:45.230 --> 01:39:47.107
(INDISTINCT)

01:40:01.371 --> 01:40:03.123
GABRIEL: Would you excuse me?

01:40:09.004 --> 01:40:10.797
I've come to say good night.

01:40:10.923 --> 01:40:13.091
Go back and talk to
the poor things.

01:40:13.175 --> 01:40:15.260
You've broken their hearts.

01:40:15.886 --> 01:40:18.180
I don't suit
this kind of affair.

01:40:19.223 --> 01:40:21.475
No. Nor do I.

01:40:22.476 --> 01:40:24.603
I wish I could go, too.

01:40:27.481 --> 01:40:28.482
(some ENDS)

01:40:28.649 --> 01:40:29.650
(GUESTS APPLAUDING)

01:40:34.238 --> 01:40:35.447
I must go.

01:40:35.531 --> 01:40:38.408
Not before you've danced.
Both of you.

01:40:38.534 --> 01:40:39.910
I insist.

01:40:43.497 --> 01:40:45.165
Mr. Oak?

01:40:47.626 --> 01:40:49.127
Thank you.
(SONG BEGINS)

01:41:17.656 --> 01:41:19.658
Tell me what to do.

01:41:24.538 --> 01:41:25.998
Gabriel?

01:41:33.255 --> 01:41:35.090
Do what is right.

01:41:38.969 --> 01:41:40.804
Sorry, excuse me.

01:42:26.183 --> 01:42:27.643
(SOFTLY) Frank.

01:42:29.102 --> 01:42:31.229
Black suits you.

01:42:32.981 --> 01:42:35.150
Although a little premature.

01:42:40.405 --> 01:42:42.240
You're alive.

01:42:42.824 --> 01:42:46.495
And here I am.
Pulled from the sea.

01:42:46.787 --> 01:42:50.123
Some fishermen found me
and brought me to shore.

01:42:50.957 --> 01:42:53.335
Then I discovered I was dead
and found I preferred it.

01:42:55.545 --> 01:42:57.172
For a while, anyway.

01:42:57.464 --> 01:42:59.049
Why have you come back?

01:42:59.216 --> 01:43:00.801
The strangest thing.

01:43:02.010 --> 01:43:03.762
I missed you.

01:43:05.430 --> 01:43:07.891
You don't seem very
happy to see me.

01:43:08.183 --> 01:43:10.602
You said I was nothing to you.

01:43:10.894 --> 01:43:12.270
(CHUCKLES) Did I?

01:43:14.022 --> 01:43:18.485
Well, then.
Honesty at all times.

01:43:19.236 --> 01:43:22.155
I find myself
in need of money.

01:43:23.115 --> 01:43:24.491
I gave up
my profession for you,

01:43:24.574 --> 01:43:26.368
and it seems a little harsh

01:43:26.493 --> 01:43:27.703
that you have a farm
and a house

01:43:27.786 --> 01:43:29.871
while I'm living
off nothing.

01:43:30.038 --> 01:43:31.415
There is no money.

01:43:31.581 --> 01:43:32.999
Then sell the farm.

01:43:44.845 --> 01:43:46.179
Come home.

01:43:50.976 --> 01:43:52.436
No.

01:43:54.563 --> 01:43:57.816
I said, come home.

01:43:59.860 --> 01:44:02.487
I'm your husband
and you'll obey me!

01:44:03.238 --> 01:44:04.239
(GUNSHOT)

01:44:05.240 --> 01:44:06.867
(GASPS)

01:44:19.296 --> 01:44:20.714
(SOFTLY) Oh, my God.

01:45:47.676 --> 01:45:49.219
(FLOORBOARDS CREAKING)

01:45:50.178 --> 01:45:51.847
BATHSHEBA: Let me see.

01:45:54.599 --> 01:45:55.684
GABRIEL: If it's
any consolation,

01:45:55.767 --> 01:45:57.602
his life will be spared.

01:45:59.396 --> 01:46:01.106
Crime of passion.

01:46:28.091 --> 01:46:29.634
Morning, Liddy.

01:46:31.970 --> 01:46:33.722
COGGAN: It's a
fine harvest, ma'am.

01:46:33.805 --> 01:46:35.265
Best we've had in years.

01:46:35.390 --> 01:46:36.892
Will we have it all over
before the dew?

01:46:36.975 --> 01:46:40.395
COGGAN: We will indeed, ma'am.
Luck's been on our side.

01:46:46.234 --> 01:46:49.446
Come, Liddy,
give me a hand.

01:46:52.991 --> 01:46:54.993
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

01:47:11.968 --> 01:47:13.094
(CLEARS TH ROAT)

01:47:13.678 --> 01:47:14.846
(BATHSHEBA CHUCKLES)

01:47:14.930 --> 01:47:17.098
I'm sorry I startled you.

01:47:18.767 --> 01:47:20.268
I wanted to
tidy up for them.

01:47:20.352 --> 01:47:22.479
I haven't been here
forsolong.

01:47:25.607 --> 01:47:27.192
Are you going in?

01:47:27.692 --> 01:47:30.862
Rehearsals.
I sing bass in the choir.

01:47:31.154 --> 01:47:32.989
Yes, I've heard you.

01:47:33.365 --> 01:47:36.117
(CHUCKLING)
Then I apologize.

01:47:39.829 --> 01:47:42.666
I've been hoping to get
a chance to talk to you.

01:47:43.458 --> 01:47:47.212
We've... We've not spoken
as much as I'd have liked.

01:47:48.380 --> 01:47:49.714
No.

01:47:58.390 --> 01:48:00.642
I'm leaving England.

01:48:04.562 --> 01:48:06.064
Leaving?

01:48:07.357 --> 01:48:09.359
Going to America.

01:48:10.318 --> 01:48:12.821
There's a boat
leaving Bristol in
four days' time.

01:48:12.904 --> 01:48:14.406
I'll be on it.

01:48:14.864 --> 01:48:16.533
Now that the farm is secure.

01:48:17.742 --> 01:48:20.578
I understand I should
give you notice.

01:48:22.747 --> 01:48:25.917
No. You must go
when you want.

01:48:30.588 --> 01:48:32.841
If Ileave
first thing tomorrow.

01:48:32.924 --> 01:48:34.384
No fuss.

01:48:36.219 --> 01:48:37.554
I think that's best.

01:49:20.889 --> 01:49:22.474
(OLD GEORGE WHIMPERING)

01:49:30.231 --> 01:49:31.232
(SIGHING)

01:49:35.653 --> 01:49:37.405
(ow GEORGE YIPS)
(SIGHS)

01:50:15.276 --> 01:50:16.861
(PANTING)

01:50:24.828 --> 01:50:25.870
Gabriel!

01:50:31.334 --> 01:50:32.669
Gabriel.

01:50:33.545 --> 01:50:34.963
Wait.

01:50:49.561 --> 01:50:50.812
(PANTING)

01:50:52.647 --> 01:50:54.649
You'll think
I'm strange, but...

01:50:56.192 --> 01:50:58.486
I've been worried.
Have I offended you somehow?

01:50:58.570 --> 01:51:00.155
No, not at all.

01:51:01.406 --> 01:51:02.991
Is it money?

01:51:03.908 --> 01:51:05.577
I'll pay you
whatever you want.

01:51:05.702 --> 01:51:07.495
I don't need money now.

01:51:08.538 --> 01:51:10.039
A formal partnership, then?

01:51:10.206 --> 01:51:11.708
Nor a partnership.

01:51:12.709 --> 01:51:14.919
The farm belongs
to you alone.

01:51:15.044 --> 01:51:17.338
It's the finest farm
for miles around.

